snippet.textDisplay: If I recall correctly, almost the whole crew thought throughout the filming process that it was going to be a super corny and cheesy space drama. Darth Vader without the voice modulation was terrible, a literal walking carpet monster...none of them had faith it'd be good and moral was pretty low. The end result, however, absolutely blew the world away.
snippet.textOriginal: If I recall correctly, almost the whole crew thought throughout the filming process that it was going to be a super corny and cheesy space drama. Darth Vader without the voice modulation was terrible, a literal walking carpet monster...none of them had faith it'd be good and moral was pretty low. The end result, however, absolutely blew the world away.

snippet.textDisplay: It was great seeing you guys react to and explain the practical techniques used in the original Star Wars movies. I would love to see you react to some of the great examples of really old-school effects like invisibility in the Invisible Man (1933), the transformations in Werewolf of London (1935) and Sh! The Octopus (1937), stop motion in King Kong (1933), and the first use of blue screening in The Thief of Bagdad (1940).
